@Node Introduction

INTRODUCTION

     Welcome to InterWord Professional, the fastest word processor in
town!

     Thank you for buying an Interactivision product.  Once you've
learned how to use it, it will prove to be a flexible and powerful
tool, and one which we hope you'll want to keep on using for a long
time to come.

SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS

     InterWord only requires 512K of free RAM, and will run on any
Amiga, from the A500 up to the A3000.  The size of documents that you
can create with it are only restricted by the amount of memory that
you have available.  When it comes to spell checking and hyphenating
your documents, you will find that the more memory you have, the more
efficiently the program will operate.  Although the program will
function perfectly when loaded from floppy disk, it becomes
exceptionally user-friendly when installed on a hard drive.

     InterWord requires Kickstart 1.2 or higher.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Word Processor"

INTRODUCTION

WHAT IS A WORD PROCESSOR

     Before we start, you may be wondering exactly what a word
processor is for, and what it can do for you.  That's a perfectly
reasonable thing to wonder; after all, you've just handed over your
hard-earned cash to buy one!

     A word processor is a tool for anyone who needs to write, whether
you're a professional author creating your sixth book, or a first time
user writing a quick note to Grandma.  It enables you to type quickly
and freely, without fear of making mistakes.

     In the old days of typewriters, if you made a spelling error, you
had to get out the correction tape or Tippex and try to repair the
damage before you could continue.  If you messed up a whole line or
more, you often had to retype the entire page.

     A word processor frees you from such worries because text is not
printed as you type.  Instead it's stored in memory on disk, and is
only printed when you are completely satisfied with it.

     Unless you erase or overwrite a document stored on disk or in
memory, you can make no mistakes which cannot be undone or repaired.

     So a word processor is a care-free replacement for a typewriter;
InterWord Professional is much more besides.  It gives you complete
control over the layout of your document, with variable margins,
fonts, tabs and line lengths, not to mention justification features
which let you decide how your text should be aligned, or if it should
be left ragged.

     InterWord saves you time too.  For starters it has a 110,000 word
dictionary, that you can use to look up individual words or
automatically check the spelling of an entire document.  It also
features a unique document analysis feature called LIX (short for
Legibility IndeX).  Using LIX you can check in moments how easy your
document is to understand.  If you're concerned about good writing,
you can even check the average length of your sentences and how
frequently you've used every word in a document.

     To summarise, InterWord Professional is more than just a writer's
tool; it's an entire tool-kit!

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node InterWord

INTRODUCTION

INTERWORD IS NOT ALONE

     Naturally, InterWord is a powerful and flexible word processor,
but its usefulness would be very limited if it were not compatible
with any other software.  Therefore InterWord can import text saved in
the industry standard ASCII format.

     Furthermore, it can also import data directly from InterSpread,
the spreadsheet program.  Its mail merge facilities also mean that it
will import mail merge data from InterBase and a variety of other
popular database programs.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "How To"

INTRODUCTION

HOW TO USE THIS MANUAL

     This manual has been designed to help you to get the vest most
from InterWord Professional.  It's been split into several parts, so
that experienced users don't have to read through lots of basic stuff
that they already know.

     In the appendices at the end of this manual, you'll find a
glossary, which you can think of as a dictionary or word processing
terms.  While you're reading, if you come across an expression or word
that you don't understand, check the glossary for a more complete
explanation of its meaning.

Beginners

     If you are unfamiliar with the Amiga, or have never used a word
processor, you should read
the @{" Installation Guide, " link "Copies"}
the @{" Beginner's Tutorial " link "Loading From Floppy"} section and
the section titled @{" Printing. " link "Printdoc"}.
When you feel more confident, you can then progress to the
@{" Advanced Features Guide. " link "Mail Merge"}

Experienced Users

     If you are familiar with word processing programs on the Amiga,
you should read the @{" Installation Guide " link "Copies"} and the
@{" Printing " link "Printdoc"} section.  If you need to know about
mail merge or using non-standard characters in a document, you should
also read the @{" Advanced Features Guide. " link "MAIL Merge"}

Impatient Users

     If you are in a rush to get started, just read the
@{" Quick Start Guide. " link "Quick Start"}  When you have more time,
you should read the @{" Installation Guide " link "Copies"} and either
the @{" Beginner's Tutorial, " link "Loading from Floppy"} or the
@{" Advanced Features Guide " link "Mail Merge"} as appropriate.

About the tutorials

     Rather than waste your valuable time, the tutorials don't go into
detail about every single feature of the program.  The contents pages
list every single function of InterWord Professional.  All of these
features are described in the Appendices.  When you've read through
the relevant sections of the manual, you can look up individual
features if, and when, the desire takes you.

And Finally ...

     One final point - you know that the program is called InterWord
professional, and we know that the program's called InterWord
Professional.  To save everyone from getting their tongues twisted,
we'll simply refer to it as InterWord from now on!

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Conventions

INTRODUCTION

CONVENTIONS USED IN THIS MANUAL

     Throughout this manual, we'll be using certain terms to describe
keyboard and mouse actions. To avoid confusion, let me clarify the
expressions that will be used.

Your mouse.

     Click        - Press the left mouse button, then release it.

     Double click - Press and release the left mouse button twice in
quick succession.

     Hold         - Press the right mouse button, and keep it
depressed until told otherwise.

Your keyboard

     There are a number of occasions when two or more keys need to be
pressed simultaneously. In such circumstances, both keys will be
given, divided by a slash '/' character. For example, if you need to
press the Shift key and the letter 'k', it will be shown like this;
Shift/K. Letters are always shown as capitals.

     To simplify things, we'll be using an abbreviated form to
describe some of the special keys. The abbreviations are as follows;

     Alt     - Either Alt key
     Shift   - Either Caps Shift Key
     LShift  - Left Caps Shift key
     RShift  - Right Caps Shift key
     Amiga   - Either Amiga key
     LAmiga  - Left Amiga key
     RAmiga  - Right Amiga key
     Ctrl    - Control key
     Up, Down, Left, Right  - Cursor keys

     On a few rare occasions, it is necessary for you to press three
keys at once.  In such an event, one of the keys is always Caps Shift,
and it therefore shifts one of the other keys.  For example, the
keyboard short-cut to display the Statistics screen is Amiga/Shift/5.
Shift 5 actually produces the percent (%) character, so rather than
printing the full key combination, the short-cut is shown as Amiga/%.

     There are no short-cuts that use shifted letters, so all the
letter short-cuts are shown using upper case (CAPITAL) letters.

     One final note about using keyboard short-cuts: although we've
said that the keys have to be pressed simultaneously, that's not 100%
true.  When you are pressing the keys that comprise a short-cut, you
should press the modifiers (Alt, Shift, Control etc.) first, then
keeping them pressed down, you should also press any additional keys.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Quick Start

QUICK START GUIDE

     Before you go any further, ensure that both original InterWord
disks are write protected.

     @{" View a floppy disk. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY Disk.Pic"}

     If you're in a hurry to see what the program looks like, you can
load it in only a few minutes.

     However, you are strongly advised to make working copies of all
four InterWord disks, so that you can use those instead of the
originals.  If you plan to save anything at this stage, you'll also
find it convenient to have a blank, formatted disk ready before you
load the main program.

     If your computer is switched off, ensure that there are no disks
in any drives, then turn the power on.  If the power is already on,
remove any disks from the drives (ensuring first that the disk
activity light is off), then press the three keys Ctrl/LAmiga/RAmiga
to reset the computer.

     Find the disk labelled 'InterWord', and put it into the internal
disk drive.  After a few minutes, the InterWord Workbench screen will
appear.  Double click on the 'InterWord' disk icon, then on the large
'InterWord' icon.  The program will automatically load, and you can
begin using it.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Copies

INSTALLATION GUIDE

MAKING WORKING COPIES

     Before you eve switch your computer on, you should write protect
your original InterWord disks.  This guarantees that nothing can
accidentally be written to them.  To write protect the disks, locate
the small black protection tab at the top left corner of the disk and
slide it upwards.  You should feel a slight click as it snaps into
place, and you will be able to see right through the square hole.

     @{" View a floppy disk. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY Disk.Pic"}

     Like everything in life, the InterWord disks are not
indestructible, therefore it is prudent for you to make copies of all
the disks, and store the originals in a safe place.  If your copies
become damaged, you'll still have the original program disks in
perfect condition, and any disruption will be minimal.  You'll need
two blank disks to make working copies, so I suggest that you go and
get them before we proceed any further ....

     OK, got your blank disks?  Good, then you can continue.  Consult
your Amiga manuals to see how to copy the InterWord disks.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Disk

INSTALLATION GUIDE

FORMATTING A DISK

     As you're going to need a formatted disk to save your documents
onto (unless you're saving to hard drive), you should format one now
to save time later.

     Consult your Amiga manuals to see how to format disks.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Installation

INSTALLATION GUIDE

HARD DRIVE INSTALLATION

     If you own a hard drive, you can install InterWord in no time at
all.  Boot from your hard drive as normal and, when the Workbench
screen appears, insert the 'InterWord' disk in any drive.   By double
clicking on its icon, you can open the directory where you want
InterWord to be stored, ie, DH0:, DH1:, etc.  Then double click on the
'InterWord' icon to see the contents of the disk.

     You should now see an icon labelled 'Install InterWord'.  Double
click this, using the left mouse button.  First you can decide,
whether you are an 'Intermediate User' or an 'Expert User'.  Choosing
the 'Intermediate' level gives you limited manual control, while
'Experts' must confirm all actions.

     After clicking Proceed twice, you must choose a disk or drawer,
where you will install InterWord 2.0.  A drawer named InterWord will
automatically be created below the drawer you choose here.

     During the installation, you will be prompted for the other
InterWord disk.  Just follow the on-screen prompts and everything else
will be done for you.

     The Install program will automatically copy all of the necessary
files to the InterWord drawer of your hard drive, and it will even add
the required assignments to your startup-sequence.  If you are using
Kickstart 1.3 or less, the assignments will be added to the StartupII
file.  If you are using Kickstart 2.0 or higher, the assignments will
be added to the User-Startup file.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Loading From Floppy"

BEGINNER'S TUTORIAL

GETTING STARTED

LOADING THE PROGRAM FROM FLOPPY DISK

     At this stage, you should have made working copies of all of the
InterWord disks, and they should have exactly the same names as the
original disks.  From now on, only use the working copies.  Put the
original disks away safely.  The only time that they should ever be
used is when you need to replace your current working copies because
they've worn out or become damaged.

     If you've just followed the instructions for making working
copies and formatting a blank disk, the InterWord Workbench screen
should already be visible.  If you skipped the earlier tutorials, turn
your Amiga on and insert the 'InterWord' disk in the internal disk
drive.  After a few minutes, the Workbench screen appears.

     At the top right-hand corner of the screen, you will see an icon
labelled 'InterWord'.  Move the pointer over it and double-click to
open the InterWord window.  Inside the window , you sill see a much
larger icon simply called 'InterWord'.  Double-click on this icon to
load the program.  The disk drive will whir away for a while, then the
main InterWord screen will appear like you see it here.

     @{" View InterWord Screen. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen0"}

     That's all there is to it.  The program is ready to use!

      @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Loading from Hard"

BEGINNER'S TUTORIAL

GETTING STARTED

LOADING THE PROGRAM FROM HARD DRIVE

     If you have installed InterWord on a hard drive using the
installation instructions given earlier in this manual, you will find
that the program performs at levels that floppy disk users can only
dream about.  To load the program from hard drive, simply turn on your
computer and hard drive, then wait for the Workbench screen to appear.
When it appears, open the drawer containing InterWord and double-click
on the large InterWord icon and the program will loan in virtually no
time at all.

     @{" View InterWord Screen. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen0"}

@{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Screen

BEGINNER'S TUTORIAL

GETTING STARTED

THE SCREEN DISPLAY

     By now you have loaded InterWord, and you should be looking at
the main screen.  If you've never used a word processor before, it may
look confusing, but in fact everything has been arranged to make
things as easy for you as possible.  Let's take a closer look at the
screen layout.



Menu Bar (1)

     At the very top of the screen, there's a black menu bar
containing white writing.  Reading from left to right, it tells you
which version of InterWord you are using, the name of the current
document and the total amount of memory available in your computer.
At the extreme right of the bar, there's a small depth gadget which
can be used to switch between the InterWord and Workbench screens
provided the Workbench has been opened.

     The current document name will read 'Untitled1' because there
isn't one in memory at the moment.  As soon as you load a document
from disk, or save one that you've been editing, the file name that
you use will also become the current document name.

     @{" View screen display 1 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay1"}

The Icons (2)

     Below the menu bar, there's a row containing small pictures
called icons, hence its name the Icon Bar.  When you click on these
icons, they offer a short-cut to some of the most frequently used
functions of the program.  Reading from left to right, the icons are
as follows:

     Cut (a pair of scissors), Copy (a camera), Paste (a paint roll),
Select Document (three box files), Print (a printer) and Disk
Operations (a disk).

     @{" View screen display 2 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay2"}

Quick Status Bar (3)

     These are followed by a blank area about fifteen characters wide,
then there is a Quick Status box that indicates a number of things
about the current state of the program.  It is capable of displaying
up to seven letters, each of which indicates a different thing.  It is
extremely unlikely that you will ever see all seven letters at once,
but if you did, you would see this: S.T.C.W.B.D.H.

     Here's what the different letters mean:

     S Stands for Style, and it shows you any styling that has been
applied to the current text.  For example, if the text has been
italicised and underlined, the letter S will also become italicised
and underlined.

     T stands for Tags and when it is present, it indicates that Show
Markers (Tags), is switched on.

     C Stands for Caps Lock, and it simply tells you whether or not
Caps Lock is switched on; very useful for touch typists or people
whose Caps Lock light is broken!

     W Stands for Write, and when it appears, it tells you that
changes have been made to the current document since the last save.
Therefore, you should save the document before closing it or quitting
the program.

     B stands for Block and it indicates that a block of text has been
highlighted.  This is especially useful when the highlight block is
not on the current screen.

     D stands for Dictionary.  When it appears it means that automatic
spell checking has been switched on.

     H stands for Hyphenation.  When it appears it means that
automatic hyphenation has been switched on.

     @{" View screen display 3 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay3"}

Line Spacing (4)

     Beside the Quick Status Box, you'll see a smaller box containing
the characters LS:10/60.  If you click on it with the left mouse
button, you'll see that this is the Line Spacing indicator, and it
lets you specify line spacing in 60ths of an inch.  The default value
is 10/60ths, but you can change this from 0 to 99.

     @{" View screen display 4 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay4"}

The Justification Icons (5)

     The last four icons let you choose from the different types of
justification.  Reading from left to right, they are: left justify,
centre justify, right justify and centre justify.  Read the section on
@{" justification " link "Justification"} later in this tutorial for
more details.

     @{" View screen display 5 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND IWDisplay5"}

The Tab Rack (6)

     Below the Icon Bar, there's a ruler called the Tab Rack.  Unlike
an ordinary ruler, which is divided into inches or centimetres, this
one is calibrated in characters - in other words, each graduation
represents one letter or symbol.  No only does this enable you to plan
the appearance of your text, the Tab Rack also lets you position
margins, paragraph indents and tabs, each of which is indicated by the
present of a small marker.

     @{" View screen display 6 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay6"}

The Editing Window (7)

     The Editing Window is the grey box that occupies most of the
screen.  Because we've yet to type anything, this window is empty
except for a small rectangular flashing cursor.

The Status Bar (8)

     Running along the bottom of the screen, you'll see the Status
Bar, which is split into two halves.  The left hand side shows
information about the cursor's position within your document.  The X
and Y figures show where the cursor is in the current page, for
example X:40 Y:20 means that the cursor is 40 characters across and 20
lines down the current page.  The current page number is shown after
the letter P, whilst the absolute line number is indicated by the
value following the letter L.  The absolute line number denotes the
cursor's position in lines from the top of the document (as opposed to
the top of the page).

     @{" View screen display 8 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay8"}

The Scroll Gadgets (9)

     The right hand side of the Status Bar contains the Horizontal
Scroll gadget, which you can use to move left and right within any
text that is wider than the screen display.  The Vertical Scroll
gadget runs down the right-hand edge of the screen, and it lets you
move up and down through a document.

     The scroll gadgets consist of three elements: two arrows, a dark
grey scroll box, and a white scroll bar within the scroll box.  They
can be used in three different ways: by moving the pointer onto one of
the arrows and clicking the left button, you can step through a
document one line or character at a time.  If you keep the left button
pressed, the scroll speed will increase.

     Alternatively, you can put the pointer on either of the white
scroll bars, then press the left mouse button.  Keeping the button
pressed, you can drag the scroll bars up and down, or left and right
within the scroll gadgets, until you have reached the approximate part
of the document that you require.  When you release the mouse button,
the screen will be updated and you can continue editing.

     The third method lets you move through a document one screen at a
time.  If you position the pointer within a scroll box, but NOT on one
of the scroll bars, then click the left mouse button and the scroll
bar will move towards the pointer by one screen.

     @{" View screen display 9 " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDisplay9"}

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Text

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

ENTERING TEXT

     Now that you're familiar with the screen layout, we can begin
entering text.   As we mentioned earlier, there's a rectangular
flashing cursor in the Editing window.  When you're typing, new text
will appear underneath the cursor.  When editing text, any characters
that you type will also appear beneath the cursor, but they will push
anything beneath the cursor over to the right.

     Let's type something so that you an see what we mean.  Type the
following exactly as printed, and remember: to type capital letters,
press the Shift key and hold it whilst you press the letter that you
want to appear in upper case.  Whilst typing the example, do not press
the Return key to start the second line.

     I'm typing this example in so that I can understand the way that
InterWord works.

     @{" View the entered text. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen1"}

     As you press the letter W in the word InterWord, you'll notice
that the letters Inter at the start of the word jump down to the
beginning of the next line, along with the letter that you just typed.
This is called word wrap, and it's one of the features that makes a
word processor so powerful.

     When the program realised that there wasn't enough space on the
line for any further letters, it automatically moved the entire word
down to the next line without you having to worry about a thing.  All
you have to do is keep typing!

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node Highlighting

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

HIGHLIGHTING TEXT

     Although you don't need it right now, there are many times when
you will need to select portions of a document.  InterWord lets you
select anything from a single letter to the entire document, and there
are a number of ways to make these sections.

     The easiest form of selection is via the keyboard short-cuts.  By
pressing a single key, you can automatically select either one word,
one line, one sentence, one paragraph or the entire document.  To use
the keyboard short-cuts, the cursor must be within the text that you
want to select, before pressing the sort-cut key.  Try it now - press
the F2 key and you'll immediately notice that the last line of text
that you typed has become highlighted.

@{" View highlighted text. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWscreen2"}

     Another, much slower way of selecting text, is via the menus.  If
you give the mouse a bit of a wiggle, you'll see a red pointer
whizzing around the screen.  Press and hold the right mouse button
down.  You should notice that the menu bar changes to reveal a number
of titles.  Still holding the right mouse button, move the pointer
until it's above the word Select in the menu bar.

@{" View the Select menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWscreen3"}

A black box containing seven options should appear below it.  If you
read them, you'll see that the last five options perform the same text
selection functions that we talked about earlier.  You'll also notice
that each option has its keyboard short-cut written alongside it.

     Move the pointer down until Word is selected, then release the
right mouse button.  See that InterWord has now been highlighted in
our text.

     Yet another way of selecting text is by using the mouse, and it's
essential for larger blocks.  Move the pointer until it's over the
first word of our little document.  Now press and hold the left mouse
button, and keeping it pressed, move the pointer until it's over the
last word.  As you moved the mouse, you should have seen more and more
of your text become highlighted, until eventually it was all selected.

     The final way of selecting text is using the Set Mark option in
Select menu.  Using the cursor (arrow) keys, move the cursor until
it's on the letter x of the word example.

     Now choose Set Mark from the Select menu, then move the cursor to
the end of the document.  Go back to the Select menu and choose Select
From Mark.  Your document will be highlighted from the letter x to the
current cursor position.  This is another useful way of highlighting
large portions of text.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Moving Cursor"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

MOVING THE CURSOR

     Another essential word processing skill, is the ability to move
the screen cursor around your text.  The slow way is to move it one
character at a time using the cursor (arrow) keys.  If you press the
left arrow key, you'll see the cursor move one position to the left.
If you keep the key pressed down, the cursor will continue moving left
until you release it.  You can try that if you like.

     The quick way to move the cursor is with the mouse.   Using the
mouse, move the pointer anywhere within our (very short) document.
Now click the left mouse button and voila!  The cursor instantly jumps
to that point ready for editing.

     There are even keyboard short-cuts to move the cursor around, but
we'll leave those for now.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Mistakes"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

CORRECTING MISTAKES

     Move the cursor until it's just to the right of the full stop in
our document.  Now press the space bar then type the following:

     Although I haven't dressed the Return key, I've already noticed
that the program automatically starts a new line for me, so that I can
concentrate on what I'm typing rather than having to watch the screen
all the time.

     We've printed this piece of text on a new line, but if you
followed my instructions exactly, your should have continued on the
same line as our previous example ended on.

     @{" View the extra text. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen4"}

     Oh, no!  We made a spell mistake.  Of course you haven't dressed
the Return key!  Let's go and change that for Pressed.  Using the
mouse, move the pointer until its tip is above the letter r in the
word pressed.

     Now all that you have to do is press the Backspace key and the
rogue letter will be erased.  You'll notice that the remainder of the
line to the right of the cursor position, moves across to fill the
space left by the deleted d.  No need to worry, this is normal.  Now
all that remains is for you to press the letter p and the word will be
corrected.

     Although it may seem unnecessary, there is actually another way
of deleting single letters, so we'll just tell you about it before we
move on.  You'll notice that when you pressed the backspace key, the
letter to the left of the cursor was deleted.  If you press the Del
key, the letter underneath the cursor will be erased.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Paragraphs"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

NEW PARAGRAPHS

     Now return the cursor to the end of the text, just after the full
stop, and we an carry on.  Press Return then type the following:

     Of course, if I want to start a new paragraph, I only have to
press the Return key and I can continue typing on a fresh line. If I
want to be really professional, I should indent each paragraph as
well.

     @{" View the new text. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen5"}

     By pressing the Return key before you started typing, you told
InterWord that you wanted to start a new paragraph, so it moved the
cursor down to the start of a fresh line ready for you to continue.

     InterWord has a feature for automatically indenting paragraphs,
so let's test it out now.

PARAGRAPH INDENTS

     Using one of the selection methods described earlier, highlight
the entire document.  Now look at the Tab Rack.  Halfway between
numbers 1 and 10, there is a small grey triangle.  In actual fact
there are two triangles, but at this stage they're so close together
that you can't see the division.

     The upper triangle controls paragraph indenting, while the lower
one controls margins.  Move the mouse pointer until its tip is on the
upper triangle, then hold the large mouse button an drag the triangle
until it's just past the number 10 on the ruler.  Release the mouse
button.  As you do so, you should see that the first line of each of
our two paragraphs becomes indented until it's level with the indent
marker that we just set.

     @{" View the Indented text. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen7"}

     This feature is very flexible and, like the other features on the
Tab Rack (margins and tabs), it can be applied to the entire document
or just highlighted portions of it.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Margins"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

MARGINS

     Let's set up a margin to ensure that you understand what's
happening.

     Highlight the first paragraph in your document, then go to the
Tab Rack and drag the bottom triangle until it's level with the number
10 on the ruler.  You've just set up a margin for the first paragraph
and as you release the mouse button the text should move over
accordingly.  You'll notice that as you moved the margin, the
Paragraph indent marker moved as well.  This is because the indents
are relative to the start of the text, not the edge of the paper.
This useful feature saves you having to reset all of the paragraph
indents each time you change the margins.

     Now move the cursor to the first character of the second
paragraph and move the margin over to the number 15.  You've just
created a different margin for the second paragraph, and you'll notice
that you didn't have to highlight the paragraph this time.  That's
because the last margin in a document (ie, the one nearest to the end
of the document), affects all further text until you set another one.

     Incidentally, there's another margin marker at the right edge of
the screen, although there is no paragraph indent marker for obvious
reasons.  The right-hand margin can be set in exactly the same way as
we set the left one.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Justification"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

JUSTIFICATION

     As we're looking at ways to improve the appearance of our
document, we should take a moment to look at the program's text
alignment options.  The correct word for this function is
'Justification', and InterWord provides you with four different types:
left justified (sometimes called ragged), flush, right justified and
centred.

     Select the entire document again (try using the F5 key)

     You may recall me mentioning the justification icons when we were
talking about the screen earlier on.  Now's the time to take another
look...

     At the right-hand end of the Icon Bar, there are four icons
showing the justification options.  At the moment the first icon (left
justified) is selected and you can tell this because its icon looks as
if it has been 'pressed' into the screen, whereas the other icons are
slightly raised up.  Try clicking on the other three icons to see the
way that it affects our text.  When you've finished trying them out,
click on the second icon (flush justified).  InterWord has padded out
every line with spaces so that they all finish level with the right-
hand edge of the page.

     @{" View right justification. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen8"}

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Hyphenation"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

HYPHENATION

     Although flush justification makes our document look much
smarter, there are now lots of spaces in the eighth line.  If you feel
that this still looks untidy, don't worry, there is a solution.

     Select the entire document once more, then press Amiga/D to
activate hyphenation. If you loaded InterWord from floppy disk, you
may be prompted to insert the second disks.  After a time, the
document will be hyphenated.

     The word indent from the last line has now had a hyphen added to
it so that the first two letters have been moved up to the eighth
line, thus getting rid of those untidy spaces.  In the line you press
Return key after well.

     @{" View Hyphenation. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWScreen9"}

     If you prefer, you can switch automatic hyphenation on, so that
InterWord hyphenates your text as you type it.

     See @{" Appendix A, Extras Menu, " link "Extras"} Dictionary,
Automatic Hyphenation for more details.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Saving"

BEGINNERS TUTORIAL

SAVING YOUR WORK

     Of course, all this work is no good if it disappears forever when
you turn the power off.  Needless to say, your work can be stored on
disk so that you can retrieve it and continue work at a later stage.
Although there are short-cuts for saving a document, we'll start by
doing it the long way so that you know what's involved.  Hold the
right mouse button and select Save As from the Project menu.  As soon
as you release the mouse button, a large file requester will appear,
almost completely covering the Editing Window.  This is the Save
requester, and it lets you store your work on disk so that it isn't
destroyed when you turn the power off.

     @{" View the Save requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSave"}

     At the top of the Save requester, there are two text gadgets,
labelled Drawer and File Name.  In the Drawer gadget, you should see
the words InterWord;, this is known as the 'path name', and it tells
the computer exactly where you want to store any documents.  It's
preset to save to the main InterWord disk, so let's change that now.

     If you loaded InterWord from floppy disk, and you don't have an
extra disk drive connected, you should now remove the program disk
from your drive, and replace it with a blank, formatted disk.  Those
of you with a second drive can insert the blank disk into that
instead/  At the bottom left of the Save requester, you'll see a
gadget bearing the word Disk.  Move the mouse pointer onto it, and
click using the left mouse button.  InterWord will promptly display a
list of all available disk drives, including hard drives and
partitions.  What you click now, depends on the drive you are using:
if you put the blank disk into the internal drive, click DF0:.  If you
put it into a second floppy drive, click DF1:.  Hard drive users
should click on whichever drive name is appropriate, eg DH0:, etc.
The Drawer gadget changes to show whatever drive name you clicked on.

     Below the File Name gadget, the Files Display shows the contents
of the current drawer or drive.  If you're using floppy drives and you
used a freshly formatted disk, this could contain two file names:
'Trashcan' and 'Trashcan.info'.  Click in the File Name box and type
practicesave.  You have just told InterWord that when it saves your
document, it should call the file practicesave.  Now click on the Save
gadget, and your work will be saved to disk.  The mouse pointer will
turn into a cloud containing a few Zs.  This is the busy pointer, and
as long as it remains visible, you can't do anything further.  After a
few moments, the normal pointer will return, and you can continue.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Mail Merge"

ADVANCED FEATURES GUIDE

CREATING MAIL MERGE DOCUMENTS

     If you use it fully, InterWord can be a great labour saving tool.
The mail merge feature is particularly useful because you can use it
to create numerous letters automatically, each of which contains
unique details.  For example, let's suppose that you work for a
company that publishes books and you want to send out a letter to each
of your existing customers telling them about your latest novel.  You
could type out a letter to each customer, manually inserting their
name and address at the top of each page, but if you have thousands of
customers, it could take months to do!

     A far more efficient way of achieving the same result is by using
mail merge.  To do this, all you need is a list of your customer's
details, and a copy of InterWord.  Of course, if you are really good
at your job, you will have already used InterBase to create a database
of customer details.  Let's assume that you aren't quite that
organised, so you'll need to make a new list of customers.

     As we've just mentioned, you could build up a customer database
using InterBase, but if you prefer you could use InterWord to do the
job.  If we use the latter option, you will develop a much greater
understanding of the way that mail merge works, so that's what we're
going to do.

     Select New Document from the Project menu, and press the Return
key twice to give you a couple of blank lines at the top of the page,
then type the following:


Dear ,

I'm just writing to inform you about our new book, 'Violence of the
Hams'.  I know that you will enjoy it, and I hope that you will place
an order soon.

Thank you for your time ,

Yours sincerely,




Your name.


@{" View the first letter. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWLetter1"}

     Using InterWord's Mail Merge features, the blank spaces in this
letter will be replaced with information while it's being printed.

     As you've probably guessed already, the blank lines at the top of
the page have been left so that the customer's address can be inserted
there.  Let's do that now: move the cursor to the first line of the
document, then select Insert Mergefield from the Extras menu.  A
requester will appear asking you for the field name, so type Address
and press Return.  You should see <<Address>> appear in your document
at the cursor position.  Now move the cursor until it's just on the
comma (,) after the word Dear.  Press Amiga/1 to bring up the Insert
Mergefield requester again.  This time enter the word Name and press
Return.  Finally, move the cursor to the comma after the word time and
again insert another field called Name.  Your document should now look
like this:


<<Address>>
Dear <<Name>>,

I'm just writing to inform you about our new book, 'Violence of the
Hams'.  I know that you will enjoy it, and I hope that you will place
an order soon.

Thank you for your time <<Name>>,

Yours sincerely,

     @{" View the second letter. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWLetter2"}

     Your document is nearly finished.  All it requires is a mail
merge file to fill in the missing blanks, so let's make one now.
Before we do, you might like to save your document in case of
accidents .... (use the Save As menu).

     Then select New from the Project menu, and type the following:


Address
Name

1 Cuckoo Cottage
David Jones

27 Avenue Des isles
Hans Sturn

54 The Terrace
Jean-Claude Smith


     Notice the blank line (created by the Return key) in between each
set of data.  You MUST press Return at the end of each line.  There
should be NO spaces after the last word of each line.  You must also
press Return after the very last word (Smith).

     You have now created a mail merge file, but to use it, it must be
saved to disk.  It's essential that you use the Save ASCII option when
storing merge files.  Go to the Save As menu and save the file now,
then select Close Document from the Project menu.

     Your mail merge letter should now be visible again, but if it
isn't, activate it using Select Document from the Project menu.
Select Print MailMerge from the Project menu.  A file requester will
appear, ready for you to select and load a mail merge file.  Select
the file that you just saved, then click Load MailMerge.  Once the
file has been loaded, you will be taken to the Print menu, where you
can specify any printer parameters to be used.  If you simply print
one copy of the letter, the first address and name in the mail merge
file will be used.  Because we want to demonstrate that multiple
letters can be printed, change the numbers of copies to three, then
when you're happy with the other printer settings, click Print.

     InterWord will now print three copies of our letter, inserting a
different name and address each time.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Format"

ADVANCED FEATURES GUIDE

The Mail Merge File Format

     Now that you've seen how mail merge works, you may want to know a
bit more about the mail merge file format.

     When you use mail merge, you are actually combining a database
with a document.  A database is the term used to describe any
information stored in an ordered manner, so even if the merge file is
created on a word processor, it is still considered to be a database.

     A database consists of fields, defined by a field name, each of
which contains information of a particular type.   These fields are
then broken down into individual records.  In the previous tutorial,
the field names were Address and Name.  When you printed three mail
merge letters, individual records in the selected fields were inserted
into the document as needed.

     Mail merge databases must be stored in a very specific format for
InterWord to recognise them as such.   The database must begin with a
list of all available field names, and these must be positioned one to
a line, with no spaces after their names, and no blank lines in
between them.  For example, if you have a database containing names,
addresses and phone numbers, the following is the correct definition
format:

name
address
phone number

     The following definition would not work because all of the field
names are on the same line:

name address phone number

     The following setup would not work because there's a blank line
between the merge field names:
name

address
phone number

     Once the field names have been specified, you must leave a blank
line by pressing Return.  The actual records can the be listed, and
they conform to the same restrictions as the field names.  In other
words, one record per line, with no blank lines between records.

     All of the elements of a record must be grouped together in
exactly the same order as the relevant field names.  If you have more
than one set of record, you must leave a blank line between each set.
The last entry in a database should be followed by a line feed
(Return) character.  Here are some examples.

This is correct:
name
address
phone number

David Smith
23 The Avenue
021 655454

This is wrong because there is no blank line between the field names
and the records:
name
address
phone number
David Smith
23 The Avenue
021 655454

This is wrong because there's a blank line between records:
name
address
phone number

David Smith
23 The Avenue

021 655454

This is incorrect because the field names haven't been defined:
David Smith
23 The Avenue
021 655454

This is correct.  Notice that there are three sets of records:
name
address
phone number

David Smith
23 The Avenue
021 655454

Paulo Giaccomo
12 Mexico Street
0101 43 76 8787786

Michelle Leunetr
65 Rue De Champs
987 9876654

This is incorrect because there are no blank lines between the
records:
name
address
phone number

David Smith
23 The Avenue
021 655454
Paulo Giaccomo
12 Mexico Street
0101 43 76 8787786
Michelle Leunetr
65 Rue San De Champs
9987y 9876654

     By now, you should understand what constitutes a valid merge
file, and what does not.  If you try to load an invalid file,
InterWord will warn you, and stop you from loading it.  If you use
InterBase's Write MailMerge option to create your files, you don't
have to worry about any of this because it automatically arranges them
correctly.

     You can insert the same merge file, and consequently the same
record, as many times as you like within a document.  By the same
token, it doesn't matter in which order you insert the merge fields
(although their order within a mail merge file is of crucial
importance).

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Foreign"

ADVANCED FEATURES GUIDE

USING FOREIGN CHARACTERS

     InterWord takes full advantage of the Amiga's operating system,
so you can enter a number of foreign characters with relative ease.
There are two ways that you can achieve this: either by typing in the
appropriate ASCII code for the character you require, or by adding
accents to characters.

Accents

     Accents are added by pressing Alt/F, Alt/G, Alt/H, Alt/J or
Alt/K, then releasing the keys, and typing the letter that you wish to
accent.  For example, supposing you wish to enter the letter 'a' with
an umlaut accent (") like this 'ä'.  Press Alt/K together, then
release them and press the letter 'a'.  To get a capital umlaut 'a'
like this 'Ä', just press Alt/K then Shift/A.

     Here are the key combinations required to print the various
accents:

Name                     Short-cut      Example

Acute (´)                  Alt/F          é ó

Grave (')                  Alt/G          ů ŕ

Circumflex (^)             Alt/H          Ô ę

Tilde (~)                  Alt/J          ă ő

Diaeresis/Umlaut (¨)       Alt/K          ü ä

     As you can see, only the five most popular accents are supported,
so if you require something more obscure you'll have to enter the
character as an ASCII value.

Entering Foreign Characters Using ASCII

     If you wish to enter a foreign character which cannot be made up
using the accent above, you will have to enter it as an ASCII number.

     ASCII is a set of codes which, when converted into printer
characters, produces a variety of letters and symbols.  Although ASCII
allows for values between 0 and 255, only those between 32-255 can be
used in InterWord.  This is because the values from 0-31 are used by
the program to control special text and printing functions.

     ASCII characters 32 to 127 produce identical characters
regardless of the printer they're sent to, or the country they're used
in.  However, the actual characters produced when using ASCII values
above 127 will depend on the nationality of the character set that
your printer is using.  See the control codes section of your printer
manual to find out exactly what your printer will print when these
values are used.

     To enter an ASCII character, position the cursor where you want
the character to appear, then select Insert ASCII-Character from the
@{" Extras " link "Extras"} menu.  A text gadget will appear and you
can type in the number of the character you require.  When you've
entered the number, press Return and the character will be inserted.

     See the ASCII table in @{" Appendix D " link "ASCII"} at the end
of this manual for a list of characters between 32 and 127.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Project"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

     The following pages list the function of all menu options and,
where appropriate, keyboard short-cuts in brackets.

     The Project menu contains options relating to loading and saving
documents, as well as allowing you to specify certain preferences
relating to the program's general operation.

     @{" View the Project menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWProj"}

     PROJECT MENU - ITEMS
          @{" NEW DOCUMENT " link "Newdoc"}
          @{" OPEN DOCUMENT " link "Opendoc"}
          @{" CLOSE DOCUMENT " link "Closedoc"}
          @{" SAVE DOCUMENT " link "Savedoc"}
          @{" SAVE AS " link "Saveasdoc"}
          @{" PRINT " link "Printdoc"}
          @{" PRINT MAIL MERGE " link "Maildoc"}
          @{" SELECT DOCUMENT " link "Selectdoc"}
          @{" DISK OPERATIONS " link "Diskops"}
          @{" PREFERENCES " link "Prefs"}
          @{" ABOUT INTERWORD " link "About"}
          @{" QUIT INTERWORD " link "Quit"}

      @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Newdoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

NEW DOCUMENT (Amiga/N) - Provides an empty window ready for you to
create a new document.  Any documents already opened will remain
unchanged in their own separate windows which will not be visible
unless you have selected split-screen mode via the Select Document
option later in this menu.  If split screen mode is active, and only
one half of the screen is in use, this option will open a new document
in the other half of the screen.  You can also use the Select Document
option to make other documents current instead of the one you are
working on.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Opendoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

OPEN DOCUMENT (Amiga/O) - This requester allows you to load a document
which has been stored on disk.

     @{" View Open Doc requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWopendoc"}

     Because many word processors, including InterWord, save documents
in their own unique format, the option can only be reliably used to
retrieve text saved in InterWord or ASCII format.  Although the
program will attempt to retrieve any thing you tell it to, special
embedded control characters - inserted by other word processors - may
cause unpredictable results.

     Drawer - Default: InterWord: - Before you can load a document,
you must enter the exact path name to your file; in other words, where
it is stored on a disk.  InterWord will accept absolute path names
such as 'Textsaves:Data', or you can refer to logical devices such as
drives and assignments, eg, 'DF0:Data'.  The text gadget is not case
sensitive, so it doesn't matter if you use capital or lower case
letters of a mixture of both.

     Note: Whenever you use the Save option in the Preferences menu,
the current drawer name will become the new default.  If you don't
want this to happen, ensure that the drawer name is reset to its
default title before saving preferences.

     Document - If you want to open a file whose name appears in the
File Display, click its name, and it will be automatically inserted in
the Document text gadget.  Alternatively, you can type in the name
that you want to give the file.  If you double-click the file name,
the document will be loaded immediately.

     Disk - Click on this, and a list of all currently mounted devices
will be shown in the files display, ie DF0: DF1: DH0: etc.  Click on a
device name, and it will be entered in the Drawer text gadget, and the
contents of that device will be shown in the Files Display.  Please
note that the Disk icon does not check whether or not a disk is
present in the listed devices.

     Parent Drawer - This gadget takes you back up one directory level
within the current device.  Therefore, if you are looking at the
contents of a drawer called 'Businesstext', on a disk called
'Textsaves', clicking the Parent Drawer gadget will take you back so
that you can look at the contents of the 'Textsaves' root directory.
The drawer name 'Businesstext' will be shown in the File Display with
the word DRAWER beside it to denote that you can look at its contents
if you so desire.

     Show Drawer - When you have selected a particular drawer, either
by clicking on its name in the Files Display, clicking the Devices
gadget or by typing its name into the Drawer text gadget, InterWord
will look at the contents of that drawer and list them in the Files
Display.

     If you then save a file in the same drawer, and return to the
Open Document or Save As requesters, the file that you saved will not
be shown in the Files Display because the drawer's contents are only
read once (unless you specify otherwise).  The Show Drawer gadget
tells InterWord to re-read and display the contents of the current
drawer so that all files are shown.

     Open - Once a file has been selected, and its name and drawer are
shown in the relevant text gadgets, this option will open a new
document window and load the file into it ready for you to read, print
or edit.  If no document is already open, the selected file will load
into the current window.  Any documents that are already open, will
remain unchanged in their own separate windows which will not be
visible unless you have selected split-screen mode via the Select
Document option later in this menu.  If split-screen mode is active,
and only one half of the screen is in use, this option will open the
selected document in the other half of the screen.

     Insert - Loads the selected file and adds it to the current
document starting at the cursor position.  This option is the easiest
way to join two separate documents together, but it can also be used
for inserting ASCII text and lists which have been created with other
software packages.

     Close & Open - Closes the current document and opens a new one as
specified in the File Name text gadget.  If the current document has
not been saved, an action requester will appear saying Loose Changes?.
If you click OK, the current document will be closed, and any changes
made to it since the last save will be lost.  Click Cancel if you wish
to go back and save the current document first.

     Return - Takes you back to the current document without loading
anything.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Closedoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

CLOSE DOCUMENT (Amiga/R) - Closes the current document window.  If the
document has been edited since the last save, an action requester will
appear saying Changes have been made!. Click Cancel to return to the
document without any further action.

     If you click Save Changes you will be taken to the Save requester
where you can save the document as normal.  See Save As (below)for
further details.  Clicking 'OK' will close the current document,
losing any changes that have been made since the last save.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Savedoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

SAVE (Amiga/S) - Automatically saves a document using the Document
name shown in the menu bar at the top of the screen.  If the document
was original loaded from disk or has already been saved using the Save
As option, the path name (Drawer) used to load/save it, will also be
used when this option is selected.

     If the file has not been previously saved, and therefore is
called Untitled1 etc, InterWord will open the Save As requester so
that you can name the file, and specify a full path name.

     @{" View the Save requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSave"}

     WARNING!!!  Unless Backup has been selected, whenever you use the
Save option, the original file on disk will be over-written with the
new one.  If you've made a lot of changes since you last saved, or
since you originally loaded the document (if you haven't yet saved),
you may prefer to use the Save As option to store each file under
separate name.  This will minimise your losses should one of your
files be destroyed for any reason (viruses, faulty disks, power cuts,
etc).

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Saveasdoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

SAVE AS (Amiga/J) - This opens up the Save requester so that you can
save the current document to disk.  The Save requester is very similar
to the Open Document requester; it has the same Drawer and Document
name text gadgets, and several of the other gadgets are also
identical.  See Open Document (above) for more details on how these
features work.

     InterWord lets you save documents in its own compressed format,
or as ASCII.  You can even password protect your work with the Save
Locked option!

     Drawer - Default: InterWord:Documents - See Open Document/Drawer
for a complete description of this requester.

     Document - See Open Document/Document for a complete description
of this requester.

     Disk - See Open Document/Disk for a complete description of this
option.

     Backup - Default: Off - Whenever you save a file using the Save
option, the previous file of the same name is over-written, thus
losing it forever.  When Backup is selected, whenever you use the Save
option, the original file on disk is renamed rather than over-written.
This means that you now have an extra safety measure to ensure that
valuable data is not completely destroyed in the event of some
unforeseen disaster.  The backup file will be called <original-
name>.b.  For example, supposing the original file was called
'Textsave', with Backup switched on, when you select Save, the
original will be renamed 'Textsave.B' and the new file will be called
'Textsave'.

     Icon - Default: On - When you save a document, you may optionally
choose to attach an icon (also called a .info file) to the file that
is created on the disk.  This icon will be visible from the Workbench
screen just like the InterWord icon is.  By double clicking the icon,
you can load InterWord with the document preloaded and ready to read,
print or edit.  However, icons do occupy a small amount of disk space,
and if you don't wish to load documents in this manner, you may prefer
to switch this option off.

     Parent Drawer - See Open Document/parent Drawer for a complete
description of this option.

     Show Drawer - See Open Document/Show Drawer for a complete
description of this option.

     Save - This will save the current document using the file and
path names specified in the Drawer and Document name text gadgets.
All preferences, including margins, tabs, text styling, screen colours
etc, will be saved with the document.  The document will be saved in a
special compressed format that is unique to InterWord, and cannot
therefore be loaded into other software packages.  If you suspect that
you may want to load the document into other packages or you want to
use it directly from Shell/CL1 as part of a computer program, you
should use the Save ASCII option.

     Save Locked - If you have private documents that you don't want
other people to look at, this option is ideal.  When selected, it
prompts you for a password, and once you've entered one, the file will
be saved as normal with all preferences etc.  When you come to load
the file in at a later date, a text requester will appear asking you
(or another user) to enter the password.  If the correct password is
given, the document will load normally, if the correct password is not
given, the document will not be loaded.

     If you use the Save option (from the Project menu) to re-save
Locked files, you will be asked to enter a new (or the same) password
before the document will be saved.  If you want to unlock a file
permanently, load it into the computer, then use the Save As menu to
save it to disk.  Of course, when you come to resave it, you should
not use the Save Locked option again!

     WARNING!!!  When you use the Save Locked option, the password
that you enter is encrypted into the file that is saved.  This means
that you cannot discover the password using file or text editors, etc.
If you forget the code that you used, you're in trouble!  You'll have
to send your files back to Interactivision (with proof of purchase),
and we will un-protect them for you.  However, this service will take
some time, so to avoid the inconvenience keep a careful note of any
passwords that you use.

     Save ASCII - ASCII is an abbreviation for American Standard Code
for Information Interchange, and it's a standardised format for saving
text files.  When you save a file in this format, all special
preferences, margins and styling codes etc, are removed from the
document.  This means that ASCII files can be loaded into virtually
any other software package.  However, once you've saved a file in
ASCII format, any styling that you use will have to be added again
when you reload it into InterWord.

     Return - See Open Document/Return for a complete description of
this option.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Printdoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

PRINT (Amiga/A) - This brings up the print requester, from where you
can print out all or part of the current document.

     Printer - Shows you the currently selected printer driver.  If
you wish to change the driver, refer to the
@{" Preferences " link "Prefs"} section of this manual.

     Font - Most printers are capable of printing high quality text,
usually called Near Letter Quality (NLQ), or low quality (draft) text.
In most cases, draft mode is considerably quicker, and uses about half
as much ink as NLQ.  InterWord lets you switch between these modes
within a single document using the Font option in the Style menu.

     Because InterWord also includes a comprehensive printer driver
configuration program, if you have defined your own driver, or you are
using one of the ones provided with the program, you can also select
any other font or typeface configurations that were defined in the
driver.  These may include fonts in a variety of sizes, styles and
qualities.  See @{" Preferences " link "Prefs"} for more details.

     When printing, you can choose to over-ride all font settings that
have been added to a document, printing the whole thing in an entirely
different font.  Alternatively, you may choose to leave all styling
commands intact.  Click on the Font cycle gadget until your preferred
setting appears.

     Paper - Every printer has its own way of feeding paper to the
print heads, and may can do it in several ways.  InterWord has to
adapt the way that it prints, according to the way your printer
handles paper, and for it to do that, you must tell it which method
your printer uses.  InterWord supports the four main types of paper
feed: single sheet, continuous, automatic sheet feeder and fan fold.

     When Single Sheet is selected, InterWord assumes that you have to
manually insert each sheet of paper before printing can commence.
Therefore, the program will pause after each page has been printed,
and prompt you to insert a fresh sheet of paper.

     Continuous paper assumes that you are using a roll of paper with
no breaks or perforations in it.  When printing on this type of paper,
InterWord will perform a single line feed between pages, but will not
pause until the entire print job is finished.  When Sheet Feeder is
selected, InterWord will automatically eject each page as it is
printed, and will continue to print uninterrupted until the entire
print job is completed.  If Fan Fold is selected, InterWord will print
in the same way as with Continuous mode, except that it will perform
sufficient line fees to skip past the perforations between each fan
fold page.

     Please note, that it is essential for you to specify the correct
page length in both your printer's preferences, and InterWord's Set
Page Length option which can be found in the Layout menu. If the wrong
length is specified, the above options are likely to produce
unpredictable results.

     From Page: - If the current document has many pages, InterWord
lets you specify the range to be printed, for example pages 23 to 34.
This is where you specify the first page that you want printed.

     All/Even/Odd - Generally, people only print on one side of a
piece of paper, however, if you want to print on both sides, InterWord
can accommodate your wishes.  It would be quite inconvenient, and
perhaps rather tricky, to print both sides of a sheet sequentially,
turning the paper over in between.  For this reason, InterWord lets
you print all the odd numbered pages first, then all the even numbered
pages.  This feature is especially valuable if you are using an
automatic sheet feeder, because it means that once the even numbered
pages have been printed you simply have to reload the printed sheets
back to front and they will be printed automatically.

     Use the cycle gadget to select which pages are to be printed.  If
you select All, every page in your document will be printed
sequentially, starting with page 1 and continuing with pages 2, 3, 4,
5 etc.  If you select Even, only the even numbered pages in your
document will be printed, starting with page 2 and continuing with
pages 4, 6, 8, 10 etc.  If you select Odd, only the odd numbered pages
in your document will be printed, starting with page 1 and continuing
with pages 3, 5, 7, 9 etc.

     Note, when using Odd and Even to print on both sides of your
paper, it doesn't matter whether you start by printing the odd or even
pages first, just so long as you keep the pages in the right order.

     Number of Copies - Indicates the number of copies to be printed.
If it comprises more than one page, the entire document will be
printed (taking account of the All/Even/Odd setting), before any
additional copies are begun.

     Perform Line Feed - Tells the printer to move the paper up one
line.

     Perform Form Feed - Tells the printer to move the paper up to the
end of the current page.

     Print - When you are satisfied with the Print settings, this
gadget tells the printer to begin printing.  If you wish to interrupt
once printing has begun you can do so by clicking Cancel.

     If you select Cancel once a print job has started, although
InterWord will immediately send a stop command to the printer, the
printer may have already stored a substantial amount of text in
memory.  This means that the printer may continue to print many pages
after you have clicked Cancel.  If your printer uses a print buffer,
you are advised to take it off-line and flush its memory out when you
select Cancel. If your printer does not have a flush function, you
should turn its power off.

     Cancel - Resets the printer configurations to their previous
setting and exits the Print menu without any further action.  If you
have started a print job, Cancel will stop the job and return you to
the Print requester.  See Print (above) for more details.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Maildoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

PRINT MAIL MERGE - Merges the specified data file with the current
document, then prints it.

     When you select this option, a mail merge file requester will
appear through which you must specify the data file to be loaded and
merged with the current document.  When you are satisfied with the
selected file name, click Load Mail Merge to load the file.  Provided
the file is of the correct format, you will then be taken to the Print
requester where the document will be treated in exactly the same way
as any other.  In other words, you can still specify the type of
paper, fonts to be used etc.

     When you're satisfied with the printer configuration, click Print
and the document will be printed.  If you wish to stop printing at any
time, simply click Cancel.

     Find out about this option in much more detail by referring to
the Advanced Features Guide  - @{" Creating Mail Merge Documents "
link "Mail Merge"}.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Selectdoc"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

SELECT DOCUMENT (F9) - InterWord is capable of handling up to 50
documents in memory simultaneously.

     Choose which documents you want to work on, and what part of the
screen they should occupy with the Select Document option.

     @{" View Select Document requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSelectdoc"}

     When more than one document is in memory, this option lets you
select which ones you wish to become current.  Because InterWord lets
you see two documents on the screen at the same time, the three
gadgets at the left of this requester let you decide which part of the
screen the selected document will occupy.  To select a document, click
on the gadget you require, then click on the document name.

     The gadgets are:

     Full Screen - The selected document will occupy the full screen.

     Top Part - The selected document will only occupy the top half of
the screen, leaving the bottom half free for another one.

     Bottom Part - The selected document will only occupy the bottom
half of the screen, leaving the top half free for another one.

     Cancel - Exits the document selection menu without taking any
action.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Diskops"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

Disk Operations (F10) - This menu contains all of the options found in
both the Open Document and Save As menus.  There are also 3 additional
options which are described below:

     Make Drawer - Allows you to make a new drawer on any drive.  A
text requester will appear into which you can type the name of the
drawer you want to create.

     Delete - Allows you to delete the file specified in the File Name
text gadget at the top of the requester.  An action requester will
appear containing the file to be deleted.  Click OK to delete, or
Cancel to abort the operation.

     Rename - Allows you to rename the file specified in the File Name
text gadget at the top of the requester.  A text requester will appear
containing the current name, which you can either delete or edit.
Once you're satisfied with the new name, press Return or click OK.
Click Cancel to abort the operation.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Prefs"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

PREFERENCES (Amiga/K) - The Preferences option opens up a requester
that allows you to alter a number of program parameters such as the
margins, type of cursor etc.

     @{" View Preferences requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWPrefs"}

     Once these have been configured to suit your own tastes, the new
settings can be saved so that they automatically replace the defaults
when InterWord loads.  The parameters are described below:

     Printer - Default: PrefDriver - Allows you to specify the type of
printer that you will be using.  The default is PrefDriver, which
means that InterWord will use whatever printer driver you've specified
in the Workbench preferences (as described in the Printer tutorial in
this manual).  If you've defined a driver using the Config program,
you should replace the name 'Prefdriver' with the name of the driver
that you've made.

     Please note.  InterWord will only look for customized drivers in
the InterPrinters drawer, so don't try entering path names in this
requester.

     Left Margin - Default: 5 - Allows you to define where the left-
hand margin should be.  If you imagine that the edge of your paper
starts at zero, the number you specify in the margin box indicates the
number of characters away from zero that printing can begin.  If your
document includes Notes, be sure to leave a large enough margin for
them.

     Right Margin - Default: 75 - Allows you to define where the right
hand margin should be.  The number you specify in the Right Margin box
indicates the number of characters away from zero that printing must
end.

     Indent - Default: 0 - InterWord is capable of automatically
indenting new paragraphs.  You can specify any figure you like,
provided it is less than the right margin.  Bear in mind that indents
are not absolute, they are relative to the left margin, and move
according to its position.  In other words, with a left margin of 0,
an indent of 5 means that new paragraphs will begin five characters
from the edge of the page.  However, set the left margin at 10, and an
indent of 5 means that new paragraphs will be printed 15 characters
away from the absolute edge of the paper.

     Flash Per Sec - Default: 3 - The cursor constantly flashes on and
off so that you can always find it quickly.  This option lets you
determine the rate at which it flashes, between one and ten times per
second.

     Cursor Type - Default: Block - The default cursor is very easy to
see, but if you prefer something less intrusive, underline is the
answer.  Click on the cycle gadget to toggle between the two.

     Auto Back-up - Default: No - If you select Yes by clicking on the
cycle gadget, InterWord will automatically save your document at
regular timed intervals.  This enables you to work without fear or
losing too much in the event of a power disruption or any other
disaster.  The frequency with which this option saves your files, is
specified in the Back-up Interval gadget.

     Back-up Interval - Default: 5 - When auto back-up is switched on,
the figure given in this box determines how often (in minutes),
InterWord will save your document.

     Back-up File Name - Default: InterWord:Documents/InterWordBackup
- When using Auto Back-up a separate file name is used purely for the
back-ups.  You can specify the file name in this box.  Note, the file
name given for auto back-ups does not alter the document's name.
Therefore, if you save the document using the Save option, it will be
saved via the path name that was used to load it, or under which it
was last saved.

     Sound - Default: On - InterWord sometimes needs to give you
warnings about things that you are attempting to do.  These warnings
may be given as an audible beep and/or as a visible flash on the
screen.  This option lets you toggle the sound on and off.

     Flash - Default: Off - InterWord sometimes needs to give you
warnings about things that you are attempting to do.  These warnings
may be given as an audible beep, and or as a visible flash on the
screen.  This option lets you toggle the screen flash on and off.

     Use - Allows you to use the new Preferences without saving them
to disk and making them permanent.

     Save - When you have set the Preferences according to your
tastes, this gadget will save then to your InterWord drawer, either on
floppy or hard disk.  These preferences will then be used
automatically each time you load the program.  Preferences are saved
using the file name 'iwprefs'.

     Special Note - When you save the Preferences, the current path
name as specified in the Drawer text gadget of the Disk Operations,
Open Document and Save As menus, will also be saved.  It then becomes
the default directory for all subsequent loading and saving
operations.  The current dictionary Set Up will also be saved.

     Cancel - Resets the Preferences to their previous configuration
and exits the Preferences requester without further action.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "About"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

ABOUT INTERWORD (Amiga/T) - Naturally, this option tells you a little
more about the program and its copyright holders.  It also tells you
exactly how much Chip and Fast RAM you have available.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Quit"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - PROJECT MENU

QUIT INTERWORD (Amiga/Q) - Allows you to quit the program, freeing up
any memory that it occupied.  If there are any documents in memory
which have been altered since the last time they were saved, the
program will offer you the opportunity to save them before closing
down.

     If you click Cancel at this stage, you will be returned to
InterWord and you can continue editing the documents as before.

     If you select Save Changes, the Save requester will appear so
that you can save your work.

     If you click OK, InterWord will close, and any changes that were
made since the last save will be lost.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Edit"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

EDIT MENU

     The Edit menu contains options primarily concerned with the large
scale manipulation and formatting of text blocks.

     @{" View the Edit menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWEdit"}

     CUT (Amiga/X) - Copies any highlighted text into the copy buffer
(the clipboard), and erases it from the document.  Anything that was
already stored in the copy buffer will be destroyed.

     COPY (Amiga/C) - Copies the highlighted text into the copy
buffer.  Anything that was already stored in the copy buffer will be
destroyed.

     PASTE (Amiga/V) - Places the contents of the copy buffer into the
document at the cursor position.  The copy buffer will remain
unchanged.

     ERASE (Amiga/E) - Deletes all highlighted text.

     INITIALIZE MARGIN - Rests the margins of all highlighted text to
the default setting as specified in the Preferences.

     REMOVE ALL TABS (Amiga/:) - Removes all tab markers from the
highlighted portion of text.  The tabs will be converted into carriage
returns so that you can quickly re-align your text.

     STORE MARGIN (Amiga'>) - Stores the current margin settings in
one of five numbered buffers, for later retrieval with the Use Margin
command.

     USE MARGIN (Amiga/<) - Retires a numbered margin setting (1-5)
and applies it to the document from the cursor position.  If a block
of text is highlighted, only the selected text will be affected.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Select"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

SELECT MENU

     The options in the Select menu are all connected with
highlighting portions of text.

     @{" View the Select menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSelect"}

     SET MARK (Amiga/,) - Sets the starting position for a block of
text to be highlighted using the Select From Mark option.

     SELECT FROM MARK (Amiga/.) - Highlights a block of text between
the start marker created with the Set Mark command to the current
cursor position.

     WORD (F1) - Highlights the word in which the cursor resides.

     LINE (F2) - Highlights the line in which the cursor resides.

     SENTENCE (F3) - Highlights the sentence in which the cursor is.
A sentence ends with a period (full stop), a colon, a question mark or
an exclamation mark.

     PARAGRAPH (F4) - Highlights the paragraph in which the cursor
resides.  A paragraph ends with a carriage return.

     ENTIRE DOCUMENT (F5) - Highlights the entire document.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Cursor"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

CURSOR MENU

     The cursor menu contains options that let you move the cursor
quickly around the current document

     @{" View the Cursor menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWCursor"}

     TOP OF DOCUMENT (Alt/Shift/Up) - Moves the cursor to the first
line of the document.

     BOTTOM OF DOCUMENT (Alt/Shift/Down) - Moves the cursor to the
last line of the document.

     TOP OF PAGE (Shift/Up) - Moves the cursor to the first line of
the current page.

     TOP OF NEXT PAGE (Shift/Down) - Moves the cursor down to the
first line of the next page.

     GO TO PAGE (Amiga/G) - Calls up a text requester into which you
can enter the number of the page that you wish to go to.  When you
click Yes, the cursor will move to the first line of the selected
page.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Style"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

STYLE MENU

     The Style menu contains options which affect the appearance of
characters in a document and can be used to give additional emphasis
to individual characters or words.

     @{" View the Style menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWStyle"}

     All of the options in this menu can be used in one of two ways:
if you highlight a block of text, then select an option, it will only
be applied to the highlighted block.  If you do not highlight a block,
the selected option will affect all text from the cursor position
onwards.

     PLAIN (Amiga/P) - Returns text to its default state with no
styling at all.

     ITALICS (Amiga/I) - Adds italics to any typed or highlighted
text.  This is italic.

     BOLD (Amiga/B) - Emboldens any typed or highlighted text.  This
is bold.

     UNDERLINE (Amiga/U) - Underlines any typed or highlighted text.
This is underlined.

     SUPERSCRIPT (Amiga/H) - All typed or highlighted text is
displayed and printed in superscript lettering, which means that it
becomes much smaller and appear to 'float' well above the normal text
base line.  The Superscript and Subscript options are mutually
exclusive, in other words only one of them can be applied to any given
piece of text.

     SUBSCRIPT (Amiga/L) - All typed or highlighted text is displayed
and printed in subscript lettering, which means that it becomes much
smaller and appears to 'hang' well below the normal text base-line.
The Subscript and Superscript options are mutually exclusive, in other
words, only one of them can be applied to any given piece of text.

     COLOUR - Lets you change all typed or highlighted text to one or
eight defined colours.  Although InterWord can only display four of
the colours on the screen at a time, all eight may be used without
restriction.  Colour codes are then sent via the selected printer
driver and your printer will print the text out accordingly.  Note, if
the Colour option in the Special menu is not selected, only two
colours will be shown on the screen at a time.

     SIZE - Lets you alter the size of all typed or highlighted text.
The sizes available will vary according to the printer driver in use,
but they may include double width and double height.  Although the
size of the characters on the screen will not change, provided you are
using the correct driver for your printer the re-sized text will be
printed as specified.  The numbers of characters per line and number
of lines per page will automatically be adjusted so that the text's
alignment remains correct.

     FONT - If you are using a customised driver created with the
Config program supplied with InterWord, you may be able to select
different fonts for your printer.  Most printers have at least two
different fonts and almost all of them are capable of printing in
draft or NLQ modes.

     Unlike other word processors, InterWord lets you change both the
print quality and the fonts at any point in a document.

     Please note that the Font menu only shows available fonts as
defined in the custom driver using the Config program.  If you're
using a standard preferences driver, you can only change the quality
(NLQ/Draft) settings within a document.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Layout"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

LAYOUT MENU

     The layout menu contains options which directly influence the
appearance of an entire page.

     @{" View the Layout menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWLayout"}

     SOFT HYPHEN (Amiga/-) - When hyphenating words that fall at the
end of a line, ordinary hyphens are inconvenient if the text may be
re-formatted at a later stage.  For example, if you delete some text
prior to the hyphenated word, you may end up with hyphens in the
middle of a line where they are no longer required.  By using a soft
hyphen, it only appears if the word falls at the end of a line.
The hyphenation option within the
@{" Extras/Dictionary  " link "Dictionary"} menu also uses soft
hyphens, and may be easier to use if a large amount of text is to be
hyphenated.

     BACKSPACE (Alt/Backspace) - Moves the cursor backwards one
character, so that you can over-type an additional one.  Although only
one character is shown on the screen, both characters will be combined
when the document is printed.

     PAGE BREAK (Alt/Return) - Forces a new page, and when printing
tells the printer to perform a form feed before continuing.

     PAGE NUMBER (Amiga/#) - Inserts the current page number at the
cursor position.

     SET START PAGE - Default: 1 - By default, the first page of any
document is numbered one.  This option is designed to be used in
conjunction with the Page Number feature, and it allows you to change
the default to any figure you like.

     SET LINE SPACING (F6) - Default: 10 - This lets you define the
amount of space (in 60ths of an inch) between lines when the document
is printed.  The maximum is 99.

     SET PAGE LENGTH - Default: 600 - This let you define the length
(in 60ths of an inch), of the paper you will be printing on, and hence
the number of lines of text per page that can be printed.

     INSERT NOTE (F7) - Allows you to type in a brief note which, when
printed, will appear in the left margin, starting on the same line as
the word to which it pertains.  Remember to leave an adequately sized
margin if you're going to use this option.

     REMOVE NOTE (Shift/F7) - Removes a note which was created with
the Insert Note command.

     HEADER - This turns header mode on and off.  When switched on, if
a header has been defined, it is placed at the top of the page, and
all other text is rearranged to make space for it.

     Headers and Footers are often used to add supplementary text
related to the current subject matter, but which would break the flow
of a piece if inserted in the main document.

     MAKE HEADER - This lets you define a header on the current page.
Once selected, a cut-down version of InterWord will be activated.
This is almost identical to the full program, although a number of
menu options, particularly in the Layout Menu, are missing.  When
you've created your header, simply select Exit Header from the Project
menu.

     FOOTER - This turns footer mode on and off.  When turned on, if a
footer has been defined, it is placed at the bottom of the page and
all other text is rearranged to make space for it.

     MAKE FOOTER - This lets you define a footer on the current page.
Once selected, a cut-down version of InterWord will be activated.
This is almost identical to the full program, although  number of menu
options, particularly in the Layout menu, are missing.  When you've
created your footer, select Exit Footer from the Project menu.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Extras"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

EXTRAS MENU

     The Extras Menu contains a miscellaneous assortment of options
which could not be categorised under any other heading.  They include
the spell checker and document statistics sections.

     EXTRAS MENU
          @{" FIND - REPLACE " link "Find"}
          @{" STATISTICS " link "Stats"}
          @{" MARK WORD/BLOCK IN INDEX " link "Mark"}
          @{" INSERT MERGE FIELD " link "Insert"}
          @{" DICTIONARY " link "Dictionary"}
          @{" UPPER/LOWER CASE " link "Upper"}
          @{" INSERT ASCII-CHARACTER " link "Insertascii"}

     @{" View the Extras menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWExtras"}

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Find"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

FIND-REPLACE... (Amiga/F) - Allows you to find, and optionally
replace, strings of text up to 79 characters in length.  These may be
single words or entire phrases.

     @{" View Find-Replace requester. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWF+r"}

     Find : (text gadget) - Here's where you should enter the text
string that you are looking for.

     Replace : text gadget - Here's where you enter the text string
that you want to replace any found text with.

     Match Cases - Unless specified, the Find and Replace options do
not compare any found text with the specified search string to see if
they are both in the same case, ie both use capital and lower case
letters in the same places.  When Match Cases is selected, any found
text must exactly match that of the search string.  In other words, if
the search string is 'Wednesday', 'wednesday' and 'WEDNESDAY' would
not match and would therefore be ignored.

     Whole Words - Normally, InterWord merely hunts to see if the
search string exists, and it doesn't care whether or not that string
is part of a word.  In other words, if you tell InterWord to search
for 'cat', it would also highlight the letters 'cat' in the words
'catalogue', 'scat', 'mercator' and anything else that includes the
specified letters.  By selecting Whole Words, InterWord will only find
words which exactly match the search string.

     Find - Tells InterWord to hunt downwards through the current
document for the search string, starting at the current cursor
position.  Each time the string is found, the search will halt and the
found text string will be highlighted ready for you to select another
option.

     Replace - Once a text string has been found, this will replace it
with the contents of the Replace: text gadget.

     Replace then Search - Performs the same function as clicking
Replace, then clicking Find.  Allows you to replace, then search for
text with a single button.  Click it once to Find, then subsequently
to Replace and Find.

     Replace All - Automatically replaces all occurrences of the
search string with the replacement string.  An action requester will
appear saying 'Replace all?', to which you should click OK if you're
certain that you want to proceed.  If not, click Cancel.  Once the
replacement has been complete, another requester will appear telling
you now many occurrences of the search string were replaced.  Click OK
to continue.

     Cancel - Can be used to return to the editing window.  This is
particularly useful if you have found a word using the Find option,
but it requires changes that can't be done from the Find-Replace
requester.  If Find has been used, the cursor will remain on the last
search string found.

      @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Stats"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

STATISTICS

     Find out everything you ever want to know about your document
with InterWord's Statistics options!

     @{" View document statistics. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWStats"}

STATISTICS (Amiga/%) - The Statistics option is one of InterWord's
most impressive features.  It enables you to analyse your writing
style and find out a number of useful facts about a document.  When
you select Statistics from the Extras menu, a requester will open to
display information about the current document.  This information may
take some time to generate, and will take increasingly longer the
larger your document becomes.  The information it gives you is mostly
self-explanatory, but for the sake of clarity, here's a more complete
description of each statistic:

     Length in Bytes - This is the total size of the document in
bytes.  If you save your document in InterWord format (the default),
the actual file size on disk will be significantly smaller than the
figure given here.  This is because the program uses its own special
save format that compresses your documents before saving them.

     Number of Words - This tells you the total number of words in
your document.  A word is defined as being any string of characters
which begins and ends with a space or punctuation.

     Number of Different Words - Professional writers will find this
option especially useful because it counts the total number of
different words in a document.  Great for checking your writing style
for variety!

     Number of Sentences - Counts the number of sentences in the
current document.  A sentence is any string of text ending with a
period (full stop), a colon, a question mark or an exclamation mark.

     Number of Paragraphs - Counts the number of paragraphs in the
current document.  A paragraph is defined as any string of text that
ends with a carriage return.

     Average Word Length - As its name suggests, this tells you the
average length of the words in the current document.  InterWord
calculates the average by counting every letter in the document, then
dividing this total by the number of words.

     LIX - This is another option which is particularly useful to
serious or professional writers, because it calculates how easy a
document is to read.  LIX stands for Legibility IndeX, and it is shown
as a two digit number, the higher the number, the harder a document is
to read and understand.  To assess the legibility of a document,
compare its LIX against the following table of averages:

     TYPE OF DOCUMENT         LIX NUMBER

     Legal documents               70

     Non-fiction books             55

     Newspapers and magazines      40

     Fiction Books                 33

     Children's Books              27

     This manual has a LIX of      37.

     The LIX is calculated using the following formula:

               Number of Words       Number of Long Words
     LIX =     ---------------       -------------------- x 100
               Number of Sentences   Number of Words

(A long word is one that has more than six letters.)

          Source: Helle Algreen-Ussing, Niels O. Fruensgaard & Bendiks
Skov-Petersen: Project or Report, Report Writing in project-organised
education.  Published by the University of Aalborg 1989.

     To the right of the Statistics requester, there are three gadgets
labelled Increasing, Decreasing and Alphabetic.  All three gadgets
provide information about the frequency of every word in your
document.

          Increasing - Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of
every word in the current document, starting with the least frequent.

          Decreasing - Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of
every word in the current document, starting with the most frequent.

          Alphabetic - Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of
every word in the current document, listing the words in alphabetical
order.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Mark"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

MARK WORD/BLOCK IN INDEX (Amiga/M) - If you are creating a large
document such as a manual or report, you will often need to create an
index.  This task can be extremely laborious, constantly having to
cross reference entries in the index to check that the correct page
numbers are given.  If you subsequently add extra pages to the
document, every entry in the index may need to be adjusted, thus
requiring more time and effort.

     Interactivision have anticipated this situation, and their
solution is the autoindexing feature which you can easily use to
generate an index as your document grows.  Better yet, if you change
all of the page numbers around, the index feature will automatically
keep track of each word or entry.

     To add a word to the index, highlight the required word and
select Mark Word/Block in Index.  The word is 'tagged' with an
invisible marker, and when InterWord creates an index later on, the
word will automatically be added to it along with its page number.

     As you've probably gathered, the indexing feature is not
restricted to single words; it can even handle entire blocks of text,
although you might think that adding a whole paragraph to the index
looks rather messy!

     To add a block of text, highlight it, and select Mark Word/Block
in Index as before.

     If you want to add multiple occurrences of the same word or
block, just mark each of them individually.  When it comes to
generating the index, InterWord will only print each word or block
once, but it will add a list of every page on which the word or block
occurs.

     If you mark two or more occurrences of the same word on a single
page, the page number will only be given once.

MAKE INDEX (Amiga/!) - When used in conjunction with the Make
Word/Block in Index feature, this option will automatically generate
an index for you.

     Assuming that you have already marked at least one word for
inclusion in the index, select Make Index and InterWord will scan your
entire document looking for words and blocks to be included.  All
marked words and blocks will be added to the index, along with their
page numbers.  The index is created as a separate document and can be
viewed using the Select Document option in the Project menu.  You can
then either cut and paste the index onto the end of the main document
or save it to disk as a separate file.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Insert"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

INSERT MERGE FIELD (Amiga/1) - InterWord's mail merge options mean
that you can create a document with 'blanks' left in it, which will be
automatically filled with text from a file of your choice.  This
enables you to define a standard letter into which personalised
information will be added each time it's printed.  The most common
example of this is a mail shot, where customer details stored in an
address database are automatically inserted into advertising
literature.  You may even have received such letters yourself from
companies such as Reader's Digest and Time Life Books.

     When you select Insert Merge Field, a text requester will appear
asking you to enter the field name.  This is the name that InterWord
will look for when it loads your data file.   For example, if you give
the field name 'Address', when you come to print, InterWord will
search your data file for a field called 'Address'.  When it finds it,
it will insert whatever text is listed in the address field.

     Find out about this option in much greater detail by referring to
the section in the Advanced Features Guide titled
@{" Creating Mail Merge Documents " link "Mail Merge"}.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Dictionary"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

DICTIONARY

     You need never worry about your spelling again thanks to the
massive 137,550 word dictionary and spell checker.

     @{" View the Dictionary. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDict"}

DICTIONARY - The dictionary option contains several functions
connected with checking and correcting the spelling of the current
document, as well as adding hyphenation to it.

     Spell Check - The Spell Check option allows you to check the
spelling of your entire document with the minimum of effort.
InterWord features a 137,550 word dictionary - many times greater than
the vocabulary of the average person.  The dictionary is arranged into
four parts, grouping words according to how frequently they are used
by the average person.  This is done to save you wasting time whilst
the program searches through thousands of unnecessary words.  However,
spell checking can still be a time consuming business, and we
recommend that you only spell check your document when you are certain
that no further changes are going to be made to it.  Hard drive owners
and people with lots of memory are at a great advantage when spell
checking, because the process can be speeded up considerably for them.

     When you select Spell Check, InterWord starts checking the
spelling of every single word in your document.  If it encounters a
word that is not contained in any of its three main dictionaries, or
in the user-defined dictionary, the word will be highlighted and an
action requester will appear containing the following options:

          Next - Skips the highlighted word without correcting it and
continues spell checking.

          Ignore - Skips the highlighted word without correcting it.
All further occurrences of the word in the current document will also
be ignored.  When the Spell Check has been completed, you will find
that an additional file has been created containing a list of all
ignored words.  This enables you to check that you haven't
inadvertently ignored words which were spelled incorrectly.  You can
view the ignored words file by choosing it with the Select Document
option in the Project menu.

          Learn - Adds the currently highlighted word to the user-
dictionary and skips further occurrences within the current spell
check operation.  WARNING!!!  This option assumes that the highlighted
word is spelled correctly, and is simply not in one of InterWord's
dictionaries.  This is not a particularly rare occurrent, especially
when using slang or unusual terminology such as that found in
scientific, medical or legal documents.  However, you should be
absolutely certain of the spelling of any word that you commit to the
user-dictionary, otherwise misspelt words may be over-looked in future
spell check operations.

          Guess - Suggests one or more spelling alternatives for the
unknown highlighted word.  It does this by selecting from its own
dictionaries all words which share the same first couple of letters.
Therefore, the program will not be able to correctly guess any words
which are misspelt within the first two letters.  To replace the
highlighted word, simply click on an alternative from the list of
suggestions, and the selected word will be inserted in place of the
highlighted one.

          Correct - Allows you to correct the misspelt word manually.
This is primarily used when the spelling mistake has been caused by a
typing error and you already know what the correct spelling should be.
A text requester will appear containing the highlighted word, and you
can insert the correct spelling at this point.  Press Return or click
OK to insert the correctly spelled word back into the document, or
click Cancel to return to the Spell Check action requester without
making a correction.

          Cancel - Tells InterWord to discontinue spell checking.  All
words after the Highlighted one will be left unchecked.  You will then
be returned to your position before you started spell checking.

Hyphenation - Hyphenates the highlighted block of text or the entire
document if no text has been highlighted.  As with spell checking,
this operation can take considerable time, and should only be used
once you're certain that no more changes will be made to the document.

     In addition to its spelling dictionary, InterWord also has a
substantial hyphenation dictionary.  Because you may not be certain
which words will need to be hyphenated, or where that hyphenation will
occur within any specified word, the hyphenating dictionary contains a
list of all possible hyphenation points in most of the words of your
document.

     When you select Hyphenation, soft hyphens are inserted at every
possible hyphenation point, but these will only be converted into
actual hyphens when a line has spare spaces in it, and the first word
of the next line can be hyphenated.

     If a word cannot be found in the hyphenation dictionary, it will
be left unhyphenated, and you may wish to insert soft hyphens
manually.  Soft hyphens take up a substantial amount of additional
memory (1 byte per hyphen) and if you are running short of RAM:, you
may not be able to hyphenate particularly large documents.  If this is
the case, you should manually insert them using the Soft Hyphen option
in the Layout menu.

Automatic Spell Checking - Because it can take so long to spell check
an entire document (especially if it is particularly large), you can
tell InterWord to check your spelling as you type.  If you select this
option, InterWord will compare every word you type against the
dictionary and, if an unknown word is encountered, it will flash the
screen or let out a short beep, according to your settings in the
Preferences requester in the Project menu.  This option is at its most
efficient when the entire dictionary is loaded into memory.  See
Dictionary Set up for details on how to do this.

     WARNING!!!  If you have switched both flash and beep off,
InterWord will be unable to warn you about incorrectly spelled words.
See Project Menu/@{" Preferences " link "Prefs"} for further details.

Auto Hyphenation - In the same way as Automatic Spell Checking will
check you spelling as you type, this option will add soft hyphens,
thus saving a considerable amount of time.

Dictionary Set Up - The dictionary Set Up lets you specify how your
Amiga will use the dictionary for maximum efficiency.  Because there
are so many different types of Amiga, ranging from half Mb A500s right
up to 32 Mb A4000, the way that you use the dictionary is dictated to
a certain extent by the machine you're using.  However, InterWord is
not a mind reader, and it doesn't automatically know which Amiga you
have, or how you want to use the dictionaries.

     @{" View Dictionary Setup. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWDsetup"}

     As we mentioned earlier, in addition to the main dictionary of
137,550 words, there are two additional dictionaries (excluding the
user-dictionary).  Each of these additional dictionaries contain
15,000 words, and the words are grouped according to their frequency.
In other words, the most commonly used words in the English language
are all contained in the first dictionary, whilst the next most common
are contained the second dictionary.  One or both of these
dictionaries may be loaded into memory so that InterWord can spell
check without constantly having to load files from disk.  In
additional to these dictionaries, 1000 of the most commonly used words
are automatically loaded into memory when you load InterWord.

     Here are the options contained in the Dictionary Set Up
requester:

     Start Hyphenation After Position - Default: 0 - When using either
of the automatic hyphenation options from the Dictionary menu,
InterWord will hyphenate words according to its internal hyphenation
dictionary.  If we take the word 'replacement' as an example,
InterWord will insert soft hyphens like this: 're-place-ment'.  As you
can see, the word has two possible hyphenation points, and although
only one of the hyphens will be used, this could result in the letters
're-' being on one line, whilst 'placement' is moved down to the next
one.  Some people don't like to hyphenate words after only two
letters, therefore this option lets you specify the number of letters
to be used before a hyphen is acceptable.  3 is a common alternative,
but if you don't care, leave this at its default of 0.

     Words in Memory - Default: None - This lets you specify whether
you want the most common words loaded into memory, or if you want the
program to load the dictionaries as it spell checks.  By loading the
first dictionary into memory, spell checking will be made thousands of
percent faster.  Click the first 15000 gadget if you want the most
common words loaded into memory, and click the other one if you also
want the next most common words loaded as well.  Each dictionary
requires a minimum of 250K free, or half a megabyte for both.

     Entire Dictionary in Memory - Default: No - If you have over two
and a half megabytes of memory, you can load the entire 137,550 word
main dictionary.  Needless to say, this will speed any spell checking
or hyphenation operations up considerably.  Once the entire dictionary
has been loaded, there is no need for the additional 15,000 word
dictionaries, so you should switch them off.

     Use Entire Dictionary Automatically - Default: No - When
InterWord is spell checking a document, it will automatically use any
dictionaries that have been loaded into memory.  However, if it cannot
find any words in these dictionaries, it will treat them as unknown
and present them to you for correction.  This option tells InterWord
to access the entire 137,550 word main dictionary when spell checking.
Obviously, this produces much more accurate results, but if you are
loading the dictionaries from floppy disk, multiple disk changes will
be required, and it will probably be too slow to be practical.
Needless to say, this option is irrelevant if you have chosen to load
the entire dictionary into memory.

     Load - Tells InterWord to immediately load all dictionary files
that you specify in the Dictionary Set Up requester.

     OK - Uses the current Dictionary Set Up settings, but unless you
have already clicked Load, InterWord will only load the dictionary
files when required.

     Cancel - Returns all dictionary settings to their previous
configuration and exits without further action.

     Once the dictionary preferences have been customised to your
requirements, the settings may be saved so that they will
automatically be used whenever you load InterWord.  Go to the
Preferences requester in the Project menu and select Save.  See
Project/@{" Preferences " link "Prefs"} for more details.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Upper"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

UPPER AND LOWER CASE

     UPPER CASE (Amiga/[) - Converts all highlighted text into upper
case (capital letters).  Letters that are already in upper case will
remain as they are.

     LOWER CASE (Amiga/]) - Converts all highlighted text into lower
case (small letters).  Letters that are already in lower case will
remain as they are.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Insertascii"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY - EXTRAS MENU

INSERTING ASCII CHARACTERS

INSERT ASCII-CHARACTER (Amiga/Y) - This option calls up a text
requester into which you may enter a number between 32 and 255.

     This number is then translated into an ASCII character and placed
at the current cursor position.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Special"

APPENDIX A - MENU SUMMARY

SPECIAL MENU

     The Special menu contains a variety of options which relate to
the way that the program actually appears.  These options are mostly
aesthetic, and although they affect your documents, they can make your
working environment more comfortable.

     @{" View the Special menu (1). " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSpecial1"}

     INTERSPREAD IN FRONT (Amiga/') - InterWord is just one of a suite
of programs which have been designed to work together.  If you have
loaded @{" InterSpread " link "InterSpread"}, the Interactivision
spreadsheet program, this option will bring it to the foreground so
that you can use it.  There is a complimentary option in InterSpread
which will bring InterWord back to the foreground.

     When the two programs are running simultaneously, InterSpread can
pass data directly into your InterWord documents, without the need for
saving any files first.  See the section titled
@{" Mail merge " link "Mail Merge"} for more details.

     OPEN/CLOSE WORKBENCH (Amiga/~) - If you have enough memory, the
Workbench screen can be opened at the same time as InterWord.
Although both screens cannot be active at the same time, you can
switch back and forwards between them using the depth gadget at the
top right-hand corner of each screen.  InterWord does not open the
Workbench automatically when you load the program, so this option can
be used to open it if required.  If, subsequently, you find yourself
running short of memory, the same option can be used to close the
Workbench again.

     SHOW/HIDE MARKERS (F8) - Whenever you create a document in
InterWord, invisible markers are used to control features such as
margins, text styling, colours and even basic functions such as
carriage returns and tabs.  At times, you may wish to see exactly
where these markers are located, and which ones have been used.  This
option will reveal all invisible markers (in bold letters), so that
they can be edited in the same way as ordinary text.

     For example, a line feed (carriage return) marker is shown like
this (LF). Although it occupies four spaces, it is treated as a single
character.  Therefore, if you position the cursor to the right of the
last bracket and press backspace, the entire marker will be deleted.

     When the markers are visible, onscreen justification is
temporarily suspended.  Although your document is still justified, the
space occupied by the markers tends to produce unusually long lines.
If you want to hide the markers, select the same option again.

     Although it is sometimes useful to see the markers, it makes it
very difficult to assess how a printed document will look.

     SCREEN

          @{" View the Special menu (2). " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWSpecial2"}

          Colour - This toggles between two and four colour screen
display mode.  If selected, a check mark appears beside the menu
option and four colours are used for the InterWord screen display.  If
unselected, only two colours will be used.  This will affect the way
that InterWord displays text which has been altered using the Colour
option in the Style menu.

          Interlace - Switches from medium resolution to interlaced
screen display mode.  This lets you see more text on the screen at a
time, but unless you have a flicker fixer or high persistence monitor,
the screen will appear to flicker and may be unpleasant on your eyes
with prolonged use.

          9 Pixel - The standard screen display uses characters
created on a matrix which is eight pixels high.  When using bold,
underline, subscript or superscript, the tops and bottoms of letters
may appear to merge into each other slightly.  To overcome this, the 9
pixel option adds an extra space one pixel high between each line.

          Palette - Allows you to customise the screen colours to your
own preferences.  When you select this option, a requester will appear
containing the four possible colours used by InterWord, above which
are three RGB (red, green, blue) sliders that you can use to change
them.

          @{" View the Palette menu. " RXS "ADDRESS COMMAND DISPLAY IWPalette"}

          A quick glance around the screen will indicate which colours
are used for which part of the display.  To change a colour, click on
the appropriately coloured box at the bottom of the Palette requester,
and that colour should appear in the current colour box at the left of
the requester.  Using the RGB sliders, you can now alter the colour to
any of the 4096 colours that the Amiga is capable of displaying.  When
you are happy with your selection, click OK, and the new palette will
be used.  If you change your mind about any alterations, provided you
haven't already left the Palette requester, you can click Reset to
restore the colours to the way there were before you starting changing
them.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

