@Node "Keys Short"

APPENDIX B - KEYBOARD SHORT-CUTS

NON-MENU SHORT-CUTS

MOVING AROUND IN A DOCUMENT:

     Move cursor up a line - Up
     Move cursor down a line - Down
     Move cursor one character to the left - Left
     move cursor one character to the right - Right
     Move cursor to start of line - Shift/Left
     Move cursor to end of line - Shift/Right
     Move cursor to start of previous paragraph - Alt/Up
     Move cursor to start of next paragraph - Alt/Down
     Move cursor to start of previous word - Alt/left
     Move cursor to start of next word - Alt/Right

ACCENTS:

Acute (é)      Alt/F Then release and press the letter to be accented
Grave (ŕ)      Alt/G Then release and press the letter to be accented
Circumflex(^)  Alt/H Then release and press the letter to be accented
Tilde (~)      Alt/J Then release and press the letter to be accented
Diaeresis/
  Umlaut (ü)   Alt/K Then release and press the letter to be accented

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

@Node "Glossary"

APPENDIX C - GLOSSARY

Alignment - See Justification.

Backspace - Backspace has two meanings in InterWord.  If you press the
backspace key on its own, it will delete the character to the left of
the cursor.  If you select the Backspace option from the Layout menu,
it moves the cursor back one position, and lets you overlay one
character on another, thus creating a combination of both.  The
combined character will only be visible when it is printed.

Current - This expression mainly applies when talking about the status
of a document.  InterWord can handle up to 50 of them at a time, or
which two may be visible simultaneously.  However, obviously you can
only physically work on one document at a time.  Whichever one the
cursor resides in, is known as the current document.  All menu, mouse
and keyboard operations only apply to the current document.

Cursor - The cursor is the small flashing block or line that indicates
where text will appear on the screen when a key is pressed.

Cycle Gadget - A cycle gadget offers you a way of choosing one of
numerous options without having to display all of them at once.  Each
time you click the gadget, the next option is displayed, and when you
are happy with the current option, simply stop clicking it.

Delete - Like backspace, delete has two meanings.  If you simply press
the Del key, the character beneath the cursor will be erased.
Alternatively, you can highlight a block of text and select Delete
from the Edit menu, erasing the entire block.  Once text has been
deleted, it cannot be recovered.  If you select a file name, then
select Delete from the Disk Operations menu, the file will be
permanently erased.

Document - Document is the name given to any text created or stored in
InterWord, from a single letter to a one hundred page manual.  It's a
simple generic term used as a substitute for all other expressions
(such as manuscript, essay, letter, paper, thesis, report, etc) which
are used to describe a piece of writing.

File Name - The identifying title given to any file stored on disk or
in RAM, regardless of its type.  File names are obviously essential so
that you can distinguish one file from another.

Gadget - Although the word gadget may have various meanings according
to the program being used, in InterWord a gadget is a button that
performs a particular function when clicked upon using the mouse.

Highlight - A highlight is simply a way of indicating that something
has been selected, be it a block of text or a menu option.  Highlights
are usually shown in inverted (negative) colours.

Hyphen - Hyphens are small horizontal dashes like this '-', and they
serve two purposes.  Their primary purpose is grammatical, because
they are used instead of a space to link two words together to form an
accepted expression.  For example, bit-map, 24-bit, high-tech, etc.

     Their other purpose is to break up long words which would
otherwise form the first word of a new line, resulting in unnecessary
spaces in the line above.

     For example, here's a piece of text, without and with
hyphenation.
InterWord is an interesting program, that deserves great distinction.
In-ter-Word is an in-ter-est-ing pro-gram, that de-ser-ves great dis-
tinc-tion.

Icon - An icon is a small picture designed to illustrate its function
or contents.

Justification - Justification describes the way that text is aligned
on the page in relation to the page margins.  In other words, should
the text be lined up with the left or right margins, or both, or
should it perhaps be aligned with the centre of the screen so that the
ends of the text are equidistant from each margin.

Keyboard short-cut - A combination of keys, which when pressed,
perform a function or operation that would otherwise require use of
the mouse and usually a menu selection.

LIX - An acronym for Legibility IndeX.  LIX is a way of quickly
assessing how easy a document is to read and understand.

Load - To transfer a file or document from disk or RAM and into
InterWord's work memory.

Mail Merge - The automatic incorporation of text from a data or mail
merge file directly into a document as it is printed, thus creating
customised letters containing personalised text, without actually
entering the personal text by hand.  If the data or mail merge file
contains multiple records, multiple documents may be printed, each of
which contains unique text.

Margin - A page has absolute dimensions beyond which text cannot be
printed, either because the printer's heads cannot move any further or
because if they could, they would be printing off the edge of the
paper.  Margins are user-defined borders within the absolute
dimensions of the page, which create areas of white space around a
document both on the screen, and on paper.

Markers - Sometimes known as Tags or Style Tags, markers are invisible
codes hidden in the text of a document to activate and deactivate
certain functions.  All of the following operations use markers:
margins, tabs, text styling (bold, italics, etc), return (line feed),
Forced form feed, justification, changes in front, size changes etc.

Paragraph Indent - Although modern typography often requires that
paragraphs are only separated by a blank line, conventional grammar
dictates that the first word of each new paragraph should be indented
slightly from the main body of the text.  The amount of indentation
varies, but three to five characters is common.

Pointer - The small red arrow controlled by the mouse and use to make
selections from menus or on-screen text.

Requester - Any window which appears and requires you to take some
action.

Save - In InterWord, save means to store the current document on disk
or in RAM (Random Access Memory).

Style tag - A Merger which indicates that the appearance of subsequent
text has been modified.  Text styles include bold, underline and
superscript.

Tab - You can think of a tab as a way for easily columnating or
aligning text.  Tab markers (small downward facing triangles) may be
placed on the Tab Rack, and when the Tab key is pressed, the cursor
will jump to the next marker.  If there are no more markers, the
cursor will move to the start of the next line.  Although pressing Tab
essentially achieves the same result as pressing the space bar until
the cursor is in position, tab markers only occupy a single
character's worth of space.  Therefore, if you delete one, any text
positioned by the tab will return to the point on the page where the
tab key was originally pressed.

Tags - See Markers

Text gadget/requester - Text gadgets and requesters appear when you
need to enter some text so that InterWord can perform an operation.
For example, when you select Page Number from the Layout menu, a text
gadget/requester appears so that you can enter the starting page
number.

     @{" Contents " link "Contents"}

@Endnode

